				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/personface" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(576333); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=576333&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164127" alt="Personface" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=576333)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/personface" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(576333); return false;" >Personface</a></span> <span class="odate time_1308299818 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">17 Jun 2011 08:36</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1180243">
									

<p>As much as I love the core concept - the derivation of SCPs from a core crack in reality, becoming ever more elaborate and complex, I can't agree with the effect this has on the overall tone of the Foundation. A substantial portion of the fear generated by many SCPs (such as the Zombie Plague or the Stairwell, both explicitly referenced in the article, or even less significant or deadly examples such as the key) is derived from the Lovecraft principle - the idea that true fear lies in the unknown. I have spent many a fearful hour speculating on the dark origins of these various examples, and sudden containments aside this SCP removes much of the unknown from the site itself, rendering previously inconceivable, incomprehensible (and enjoyable for those qualities) SCPs merely the work of man. Consider the secluded telephone, or the ticket that tears people from reality, or the pilgrimage plane - think of what is lost from those when we lose sight of the unknown, of those shadowy moments of speculation. So with all due respect, because in terms of quality it is actually written rather well, I can't well condone an entry that renders a large number of the series effectively known and understood. Downvoted reluctantly.</p>

							</div>

								
					
