			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1180742)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1180742">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=732274&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164127" alt="thedeadlymoose" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=732274)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;" >thedeadlymoose</a></span> <span class="odate time_1308347385 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">17 Jun 2011 21:49</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1180742">
									

<p>This is <em>exactly</em> why the final paragraph makes this story.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>They just… were, one day. They were in containment, and they'd always been in containment.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>With that, even the most innocuous Safe-class SCP becomes frightening.</p>
<p>Take <a href="/scp-341">SCP-341</a>, &quot;A Collection of Extrasolar Orreries&quot;. Probably as harmless as you can possibly get for an SCP. No dark corners of the night there, right?</p>
<p>But&#8230; wait. It's unlikely that Mann's researchers made <em>that</em> - why even make them an SCP? Toss it aside with the other rough drafts. Which means it was one of the SCPs that showed up, and had always been there, on display in the exhibition hall of Reliquary Research and Containment Site-76 for all to see, complete with own SCP status and number.</p>
<p>Can you <em>imagine</em>?</p>
<p>And even the SCPs they did make. Maybe they deluded themselves into thinking these things were their creations at first. But they're too&#8230; whole cloth. Too neat. Too starkly different from each other. What are the odds that these things turned out so different and so fucked up and so <em>complete</em>?</p>
<p>This implication gives the final lines even more impact:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>We're not in control anymore. We never were.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It might be incorrect to say these things were <em>man-made</em>. Rather, men and women found the loose strings of reality and tugged. And these are what came out.</p>

							</div>

								
					
